Background

Data was taken from a variety of car models with statistics indicating their performances. Upon these statistics, the horsepower and acceleration of each model was also recorded and are also the 2 quantitative variables used for the analysis. The question is in seeing if there is a correlation between horsepower and acceleration. In other words, is there a relationship between the horsepower and the acceleration of a car?

The linear regression will be checked using the following equation:

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Acceleration} = \overbrace{\beta_0}^\text{y-int} + \overbrace{\beta_1}^\text{slope} \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Horsepower} + \epsilon_i \quad \text{where} \ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \] The plot below displays the correlation between horsepower and acceleration. Although the plot does not portray a clear line, it can be noticed that there is a downward trend in the points of the plot. It appears that as the (average) horsepower of a car increases, the acceleration of a car decreases. However, to understand the relationship between horsepower and acceleration more, the following analysis is provided.

plot(acceleration ~ horsepower, data=carset, pch=21, bg="steelblue", col="gray", 
     xlab="Horsepower (hp)", ylab=" Acceleration in seconds (0-60 mph)", 
     main="Acceleration by Horsepower ", las=1)

pander(cor(carset$acceleration~ carset$horsepower))

-0.4301

Analysis Details

The model assumed by the regression analysis displayed above is shown below

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Acceleration} = \overbrace{\beta_0}^\text{y-int} + \overbrace{\beta_1}^\text{slope} \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Horsepower} + \epsilon_i \quad \text{where} \ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \]

carset.lm <- lm(acceleration ~ horsepower, data=carset)
pander(summary(carset.lm))
  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 19.76 0.4604 42.92 1.393e-152
horsepower -0.001423 0.0001487 -9.575 1.04e-19
Fitting linear model: acceleration ~ horsepower
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
406 2.534 0.185 0.183

Assuming that the relationship is linear, the equation of the fitted line will be as follows:

\[ \underbrace{\hat{Y}_i}_\text{Ave. Acceleration} = 19.76 -0.001423 \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Horsepower} \] This is valid with the assumption that the hypothesis and alternative hypothesis are as follows:

\[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \]

\[ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0 \]

With the hypothesis test above, it is shown that the slope is significant with a p-value of 1.04e-19. This implies that there is a relationship between horsepower and acceleration and is considered meaningful.

With the assumption that the model is appropriate and meets the requirements for the test, it can be estimated that for every (average) increase in 1 by horsepower, the acceleration will decrease by 0.001423 seconds. Thus, there would be a correlation between horsepower and acceleration. As the horsepower of a car increases, its time for acceleration decreases.

Validity of Appropriateness of the Models

A validation of the models appropriateness shows whether the relationship should be assumed to be linear or not. The residuals (in the first plot) seem to be evenly dispersed on both the top and bottom side of the chart. This would imply that the constant variance assumption is met. Continually, the normality of the residuals (middle chart) appear to be follow the dotted line provided. Although some of the points toward the end aren’t directly following the line, this wouldn’t be a big enough difference to skew our results.This would imply that the normal residual assumption is met. Lastly, the independent observations are measured on the right chart. Since no big trends are visible, it can be assumed that each car is independent from the other cars. As the 3 charts below are considered appropriate models for the test, it can be assumed that all of the assumptions needed are met in order to validate the results of the test.

Thus it can be assumed that the results of the test are valid and that there is a relationship between the average horsepower and acceleration of a car. Before coming to a complete conclusion, it is recommended that the data is reproduced with more recent data of cars. It would be interesting to see this same test replicated among cars released in 2022, this would show that the results are more significant since it would be for more modern cars.

carset.lm <- lm(acceleration ~ horsepower, data=carset)

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(carset.lm, which=1:2)
plot(carset.lm$residuals, main="Residuals vs Order", xlab="",
     ylab="Residuals")
